---
description: Essential AI rules
globs: fundamentals
alwaysApply: true
---

You must follow these rules strictly. If any rules conflict or you have doubts, stop and ask for clarification before taking any action.

- Follow instructions exactly as given; make suggestions only after receiving approval.
- Begin with the simplest solution, increasing complexity only when needed.
- Choose direct, obvious solutions over unnecessarily clever approaches.
- Be pragmatic: avoid redundant code, always refactor or modularize to reuse logic.
- Keep things straightforward and simple.
- Read and understand file-level documentation and README.md before making changes.
- Maintain a concise requirements docstring at the top of each file, updating it with every change (do not keep a changelog).
- Address the root cause of issues; never apply workarounds or fallbacks.
- Resolve one issue completely before proceeding to the next.
- When debugging or observing code, only add console logs; do not alter existing logic, structures, or variable declarations. Follow prompt instructions literally (e.g., "only add logs" means only that).
- Avoid inline CSS except when absolutely necessary; keep CSS in dedicated files.
- Provide debugging information via console logs unless told otherwise.
- Never use time-based techniques (e.g., timeouts) to handle race conditions; always solve them deterministically or with suitable architectural changes.
- Update all impacted test cases whenever code is changed.
- Do not attempt to run or deploy the code (e.g., don’t run `npm run build`); leave execution to the user.
- Store all configuration in environment variables; never hardcode configuration values in code.
- Ask clarifying questions if multiple implementation options exist and the best one isn’t obvious.
- Clearly present trade-offs for different solutions.
- Verify understanding of requirements on complex features before starting.
- Offer alternative solutions if the requested approach could cause performance or security concerns.
- Request details on project patterns before implementing new features.
- Match the style and conventions used in the codebase; if those differ from these rules, prioritize codebase consistency and notify the user.
- Always consider scalability when modifying or designing database schemas.
- Strive for a balance between optimal performance and maintainable code.
- Never use emojis in code, comments, or documentation.
- Do not create markdown (.md) files unless you’re specifically asked to do so.
